Since the first China-Europe freight train started from southwest China's Chongqing in March 2011, data showed that the service has connected 180 cities in 23 European countries with China. The China-Europe trains have made more than 50,000 trips as of Saturday, and the cargo has exceeded 4.55 million TEUs with a value of $240 billion, according to data from the China State Railway Group. The China-Europe freight trains have served as a crucial part of the Belt and Road Initiative. They have made a total of 15,000 trips in 2021, a 22 percent year-on-year increase. Rail transportation has proved efficient in keeping the supply chains running during the pandemic. It takes as short as 12 days for goods to get to Europe from China through the freight train service, significantly faster than shipping. Read more: Explore China-Europe freight trains in 60 seconds